# Copy to .env and adjust. All variables are optional; the defaults target a
# service running locally on http://127.0.0.1:8000.

# ── Open Climate Service (client side — read by the example scripts) ──────────
OCS_BASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:8000
OCS_TIMEOUT=30

# ── DHIS2 (only needed by examples/05_dhis2) ─────────────────────────────────
# `admin` / `district` are the public DHIS2 demo credentials. Replace with your own.
OCS_DHIS2_BASE_URL=https://climate.im.dhis2.org/climate-tools-42
OCS_DHIS2_USERNAME=admin
OCS_DHIS2_PASSWORD=district

# ── Data-source credentials (server side) ────────────────────────────────────
# These are NOT read by the example scripts. They belong to the *instance/server*
# environment, because downloads happen server-side during ingestion. Set them where
# you run the Open Climate Service (or the e2e tests, which boot an instance in-process)
# only if you ingest a dataset that needs them.
#
#   CHIRPS (chirps3_precipitation_daily) ........... no key required (public HTTP)
#   WorldPop (worldpop_population_yearly) ........... no key, but needs extent.country_code
#   ERA5-Land monthly/daily via Copernicus CDS ...... ECMWF_DATASTORES_* (below)
#   ERA5-Land *_from_hourly via DestinE Earth Data Hub  EDH_API_KEY (below)
#
# Copernicus Climate Data Store / ecmwf-datastores. The installed client reads these
# exact variable names (or a ~/.ecmwfdatastoresrc file with `url:` / `key:` lines).
# The URL and key are your CDS personal access token from
# https://cds.climate.copernicus.eu/ (Your profile -> Personal Access Token).
# ECMWF_DATASTORES_URL=https://cds.climate.copernicus.eu/api
# ECMWF_DATASTORES_KEY=your-cds-personal-access-token
#
# DestinE Earth Data Hub (register at https://earthdatahub.destine.eu/), used by the
# era5land_*_from_hourly templates:
# EDH_API_KEY=your-edh-api-key
